alihoaliho wrote:
&gt; Can someone tell me how did pages from these domain got in the ARC file?

The point of the &#39;Transclusion&#39; rule is to allow hops off your main 
scope if they appear necessary to render other pages (as with inline 
images, JS, CSS, frames).

So this rule...

&gt;           &lt;newObject name=&quot;acceptIfTranscluded&quot;
&gt; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.TransclusionDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt;             &lt;integer name=&quot;max-trans-hops&quot;&gt;3&lt;/integer&gt;
&gt;             &lt;integer name=&quot;max-speculative-hops&quot;&gt;1&lt;/integer&gt;
&gt;           &lt;/newObject&gt;

...means essentially &quot;include even thus-far REJECTed URIs, if they have 
from 1-3 &#39;transclusion&#39; hops (Embed, Redirect, Xspeculative types) at 
the end of their &#39;hops-path&#39;. However, only accept 1 &#39;speculative&#39; (X) 
hop in a row.&quot;

You could remove this rule entirely if you want your crawl to stay 
strictly on your seed/SURT domains, even if that means incomplete 
multi-URI pages.

Othr notes on your rules:

This rule is essentially meaningless inside a &#39;scope&#39;. Scoping only 
works before a URI has been network-fetched. At that time, there is no 
&#39;content-type&#39; header yet to examine. (This rule class is usually used 
places other than scoping, for example to limit operation of a Processor.)
&gt;           &lt;newObject name=&quot;htmlContentTypeFilter&quot;
&gt; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.ContentTypeMatchesRegExpDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt;             &lt;string name=&quot;decision&quot;&gt;ACCEPT&lt;/string&gt;
&gt;             &lt;string name=&quot;regexp&quot;&gt;(?i)text/html.*&lt;/string&gt;
&gt;           &lt;/newObject&gt;

This next rules rejects by URL file-extension, and may reject content 
that is likely to be link-bearing HTML (.xhtml/.xht) or be rendered in 
HTML by browser with XSLT or JS (.xml). (Additionally, .doc and .pdf 
files also include text and possibly links, depending on whether your 
crawl is text- or link-graph-focuses.) Just FYI.
